Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He hated it especially because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his company. Quietly, he stood up from his bunk, put on his combat uniform, threw on his bulletproof vest, and retrieved his belongings from the locker, being careful with a small specific box. He slung his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Everything he needed was attached to it, such as his gas mask or his special glasses. After checking his ammunition pouches, he left the barracks quietly. Outside, mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He pulled out a lighter from one pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a quick drag before opening the door slightly. In the past week, he had to come up with a lot of creative ways to wake up the men and women assigned to him. He no longer used the pre-set alarm, as it usually didn't work and only produced a faint humming from the speakers.
"Wake them up?" Cohren turned around and saw Platoon Leader Nemic approaching him.
"Yes," Cohren replied.
"What do you want to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened, and Harris, Craith, and a few others came out to meet him, already fully dressed.
"Good morning," Craith said.
"What woke you up?" Cohren asked.
"Well, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting to see what you'd come up with today again. And secondly, the assault troops, who have to get up first, can choose the morning ration," one of the men, Ravik, replied. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, Sergeant," Cohren said. He reached in and pressed a button. In the barracks, a loud, shrill alarm sounded. Inside, he heard muffled cursing and people rushing around.
"Man, Valturi," Nemic said. "You'd think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
"Well, my people from the training camp have learned," Cohren replied, pointing to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and company leaders also know that they have to get up before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal belongings to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others seemed annoyed.
"Good morning," Cohren said with a good mood.
"With all respect, Sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?" a sergeant of the assault troops asked.
"Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn't sleep," Cohren said.
"Pack up all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As a lieutenant colonel and the company's executive officer, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting the company, along with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We're not coming back here again. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack the daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company scattered quickly. They were part of the second assault division, second army. Before they were merged, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was divided, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked side by side in the light of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operating base. Most had red-tinted glass to avoid being discovered by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and ground to counter them.
“A new day and a new task for the devil dogs,” Nemic said with a dry laugh. “Where are they sending us?”
“A forward operating base outside of Ianlos. We will support the ground attack,” Cohren replied and took a drag on his cigarette. He blamed Craith for starting him smoking, but a year in the field changed people, so he said nothing.
“Shit. It's getting worse at the front,” Nemic muttered. “All the news says: ‘Support the war efforts. Send help to the Kurgan Front.’ How about sending help to the Howland Front?”
“Amen, brother,” Cohren said and flicked the remains of his cigarette into the mud. “At least we're going with the first armed platoon and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be here.”
“Did Shaw clear a ride for us?” Nemic asked a bit surprised.
“Yes. He's actually not as bad as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but you can get along with him.”
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and put on his backpack as he spoke. “All units of the Exodus Company are to meet at the West Transportation Area when they're ready. We're leaving with the first armed platoon at 0500.”
In rapid succession, he received responses from the squad leaders. Harris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they first arrived here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth, despite having only been here for at most two years. Cohren felt like he'd known them forever, although it was only a short time. They were squad leaders, but Craith had been leading the second platoon for a week, after the previous leader was medically discharged due to being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On the way to the transportation area, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of around eight Kronos combat tanks and four infantry tanks. Their crews were busy ensuring their vehicles were operational. As they approached, Cohren spotted Captain Boradin Shaw talking to the commander of the armed platoon. When they drew near, Shaw looked over at them and walked towards them, as always with a expressionless face.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster and then back up again. "The company is ready, I assume?"
